-- Japan, India, Singapore, Korea, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Previews
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-11-01T22:27:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-01/japan-india-singapore-korea-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-previews.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: The Bank of Japan will release minutes of its Oct.
4-5 board meeting at 8:50 a.m.  The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.2 trillion yen ($27
billion) of 10-year bonds today. The ministry will announce a
coupon for the new securities at 10:30 a.m.  Japan’s Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings in the morning and afternoon.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 rose three basis points to 0.95 percent, according to Japan
Bond Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.
A basis point is 0.01 percentage point.  The yen traded at 80.61 per dollar at 7:19 a.m. in Tokyo.  India: The Reserve Bank of India may boost its benchmark
repurchase rate to 6.25 percent from 6 percent today in Mumbai,
according to economists’ forecasts in a Bloomberg survey.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.11
percent. The rupee was at 44.48 per dollar.  Singapore: The Singapore Institute of Purchasing &
Materials Management will say today the purchasing managers’
index fell to 49.3 in October from 49.5 the previous month,
according to a Bloomberg survey of economists. A reading above
50 indicates overall factory output expanded.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
1.98 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2916.  South Korea: Foreign-exchange reserves rose to a record
$293.4 billion in October, the Bank of Korea reported today.
Holdings were $289.8 billion in September.  The yield on the 3.75 percent note due June 2013 was 3.35
percent, according to Korea Stock Exchange. The won traded at
1,116.55 per dollar.  Thailand: Thailand: The central bank will sell 125 billion
baht ($4.18 billion) of 28-, 91-, 183- and 364-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.21
percent. The baht was at 29.85 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Andrea Wong  in Hong Kong at 
